**TL;DR: Everything You Need to Know About Emerald Cut Diamonds**

An emerald cut diamond is a rectangular step-cut diamond with clipped corners, featuring long parallel facets arranged in descending steps from the table to the girdle.

It is the most sophisticated, most architecturally distinct, and most technically demanding diamond shape to buy correctly — because its open step-cut facets act as optical windows that expose every inclusion, every color trace, and every proportion flaw that brilliant cuts conceal.

**Live May 2026 price snapshot:**

-   1ct natural F-VS1 Ideal Cut GIA starts at **[$3,350](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28899471?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)**.
-   1ct natural D-IF Ideal Cut GIA: **[$5,840](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28453240?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)**.
-   1.54ct lab-grown E-VVS1 Excellent Cut IGI: **[$2,040](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28523264?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)**.
-   2ct lab-grown D-FL Ideal Cut GCAL: **[$4,280](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28785027?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)**.
-   Emerald cuts cost **30–40% less** than equivalent round brilliants at the same carat, color, and clarity.
-   Emerald cuts require **VS1 minimum clarity** — the most stringent clarity requirement of any popular shape.

**The single most important thing to know before buying:** GIA does not issue a cut grade for emerald cut diamonds. "Ideal Cut" on a Blue Nile listing is Blue Nile's retailer assessment — not a laboratory certification. Proportion evaluation from the GIA certificate is mandatory for every emerald cut purchase.

**Buy an emerald cut if:**

-   You want the most sophisticated, elegant, architectural diamond aesthetic in the market.
-   You prefer the hall-of-mirrors optical effect over rapid brilliant-cut scintillation.
-   You want a significant size-per-dollar advantage — elongated shapes appear larger than their carat weight.
-   You are buying lab-grown at 2ct+ — the value is extraordinary.

**Do not buy an emerald cut if:**

-   You want maximum sparkle and light performance — round brilliant leads here.
-   You cannot commit to VS1 minimum clarity — the open facets expose lower-grade inclusions.
-   You want to maximize apparent size per dollar — oval and marquise appear larger at the same price.
-   You are on a strict budget that forces SI1 clarity — emerald cuts at SI1 are almost never eye-clean.

