60919?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blog-informational" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">$121,480</a></strong></td><td><strong>10/10 — The 5ct Pricing Sweet Spot.</strong> This listing represents an incredible analytical opportunity for a premier institutional asset. Landing exactly on the 5.00ct mark with an elite D-VS1 grading profile for $121k is a massive win when compared to its 5ct siblings.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>5.07ct</strong></td><td>F-VS1 Ideal</td><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/19713756?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blog-informational" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">$138,140</a></strong></td><td><strong>6/10 — Out of Alignment.</strong> This listing carries a pricing anomaly that makes zero market sense. You are dropping from D color to F color, yet you are paying nearly $17,000 <em>more</em> than the 5.00ct D-color master stone. Skip this entry entirely.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>5.09ct</strong></td><td>D-VS1 Ideal</td><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/18249190?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blog-informational" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">$251,750</a></strong></td><td><strong>5/10 — Severe Premium Anomaly.</strong> Paying over $250k for a D-VS1 simply because of an extra 9 points of carat weight over the $121k stone is completely indefensible. This represents an astronomical mark-up that should be heavily avoided by smart buyers.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>7.01ct</strong></td><td>D-VS1 Ideal</td><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/19301085?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blog-informational" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">$392,390</a></strong></td><td><strong>9/10 — The Sovereign Heirloom.</strong> Approaching the $400k mark, we leave traditional luxury and enter high-value portfolio assets. A 7-carat emerald cut with elite color and eye-clean geometry is an exceptionally rare find globally, commanding a worthy museum-grade premium.</td></tr></tbody></table>

**The 5ct data point:** Two D-VS1 5ct emerald cuts priced at $121,480 and $251,750 — a $130,270 gap for identical GIA grade specifications. This is the most dramatic illustration in the entire catalog of how proportion quality drives price within the same grade.

The $121,480 stone likely has depth or table outside the ideal range. The $251,750 stone has superior proportions that produce dramatically better light performance. This is why proportion verification is not optional for emerald cuts at any price point.

## **Lab-Grown Emerald Cut Diamond Prices: The 2026 Arbitrage**

**Lab-grown emerald cuts start at $2,040 for a 1.54ct E-VVS1 — delivering more carat weight, better specs, and Internally Flawless options at a fraction of natural pricing.**

The lab-grown emerald cut arbitrage is the most compelling in the entire step-cut category — because the natural emerald's mandatory VS1+ clarity requirement becomes irrelevant in lab-grown where D-FL and D-IF stones at 2ct+ are available for under $5,000.

